    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-06-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-06-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="20" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Benjamin</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">John Slidell</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Richmond</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-06-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 23,
                                        1864</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <seg type="margin">[331]</seg>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I can scarcely trust myself with the
                                expression of the indignation felt by the president at the evasions
                                and injustice of the French government in relation to the
                                Rappahannock. He is of opinion that the delay in the action finally
                                taken by you on the subject went *to the extreme verge of propriety,
                                and is gratified to find that the decisive step was adopted of
                                striking her flag and leaving her to the responsibility of the
                                French government. The speech of Mr. Rouher on the 12th ultimo in
                                the French chamber, and the circular letter of Mr. Drouyn de Lhuys
                                of 4th ultimo, as given in that speech, have just reached us in the
                                Index of 19th May, and may probably be regarded as correctly
                                translated by Mr. Holze. They indicate so complete an “extente”
                                between the cabinets of Washington and Paris, that we should be
                                blind indeed if we failed to attach to these incidents their true
                                significance.</p>
                <p>I am, very respectfully, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J. P. BENJAMIN,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of
                                        State.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">John Slidell</hi>, <hi rend="smallcaps">&amp;c., Paris.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
